Then, let us also compute the equally weighted portfolio expected return during Bust using the same formula from step 4. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
{\text{Expected return, Bust}}&={\dfrac{\text{ 11\% - 5\% -8\%}}{\text{3}}}\\
&={\textbf{-0.67\%}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The expected return during Bust is -0.67%.**

We can now calculate the portfolio's expected return by multiplying the return in each state of the economy by the probability return. The following formula is used to calculate this:
$$\begin{aligned}
{\text{Portfolio expected return}}&={\text{(75\% $\times$ 16.33\%) + (25\% $\times$ -0.67\%)}}\\
&= {\text{12.25 - 0.17\% }}

&={\textbf{12.08\%}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The portfolio expected return is 12.08%.**

Let us compute the variance of the portfolio using the formula from step 7. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{V}&=  {\text{[75\% $\times$ (19.40\% - 13.65\%)}^\text{ 2}}{{]}} + {\text{[25\% $\times$ (-3.60\% - 13.65\%)}^\text{ 2}}{{]}}\\

&= {\textbf{0.00991875}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The variance of the portfolio is 0.00991875.**
